  "prompt": "What happens to you if you try to walk around Mars without a spacesuit?",
  "response": "If you were to try to walk around Mars without a spacesuit, you would face several immediate and severe dangers due to the planet's harsh environment:\n\n1. **Lack of Atmospheric Pressure**: Mars has a very thin atmosphere with a pressure about 1% of Earth's. Without the protection of a spacesuit, your body fluids would start to boil due to the low pressure, leading to a condition known as ebullism. This would cause severe damage to your tissues and organs.\n\n2. **Extreme Cold**: Temperatures on Mars can range from about -195\u00b0F (-125\u00b0C) at the poles to about 70\u00b0F (20\u00b0C) at the equator during the day. At night, temperatures can plummet. Without a spacesuit to provide insulation, you would suffer from rapid hypothermia and frostbite.\n\n3. **Lack of Oxygen**: Mars' atmosphere is mostly carbon dioxide, with very little oxygen. Without a spacesuit providing oxygen, you would quickly lose consciousness due to hypoxia and die within minutes.\n\n4. **Radiation Exposure**: Mars has no global magnetic field and a thin atmosphere, offering little protection against cosmic and solar radiation. Without the shielding of a spacesuit, you would be exposed to harmful levels of radiation, which could cause radiation sickness and increase your risk of cancer.\n\n5. **Dust and Debris**: Martian dust storms can be massive and long-lasting. Without protective gear, the fine dust particles could irritate your skin, eyes, and lungs if inhaled.\n\nIn summary, attempting to walk around Mars without a spacesuit would result in almost instantaneous death due to a combination of low pressure, extreme cold, lack of oxygen, and radiation exposure.",
